<dl id="n54141d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54141d">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54141d"> 141(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">H</font>&apos;s face is treebark <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54141d"><li>FW 279.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lf/lexlf.htm#n54141d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lf/l39lf.htm#n54141d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54141d">MS BL 47478-339</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:318 <a name="lad13" href="../../ff/fdra/lda.htm#lfd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lf/lfd4.htm#n54141d">Draft: II.2&sect;7.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Ainsi, dans le nord du Queensland, sur le fleuve Pennefather, &laquo;quand un visiteur s&apos;est rendu particuli&egrave;rement agr&eacute;able et quitte ses h&ocirc;tes pour rentrer chez lui, on taille, sur un arbre dont le bois est tendre, une effigie de lui, de trois ou quatre pieds de long, du c&ocirc;t&eacute; de l&apos;arbre qui regarde la direction de sa demeure. D&apos;apr&egrave;s l&apos;&eacute;tat de cet arbre &mdash; s&apos;il perd ses feuilles, si le vent le renverse, etc. &mdash; les indig&egrave;nes savent en quelle condition se trouve leur ami, s&apos;il est sain et sauf, bien portant, etc.&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[Thus, in the north of Queensland, on the Pennefather river, "when a visitor has made himself particularly pleasant and leaves his hosts to return home, we prune, on a tree whose wood is tender, an effigy of him, three or four feet long, on the side of the tree facing the direction of his home. According to the state of this tree&mdash;if it loses its leaves, if the wind overturns it, etc.&mdash;the natives know in what condition their friend is, if he is safe, healthy, etc.".]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 234</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
